Data Analysis and Knowledge Discovery: Exercise 2, Supervised learning¶

The previous exercise was about data understanding and data preparation, which formed the basis for the modeling phase of the data mining process. Many modeling techniques make assumptions about data so the exploration and preparation phases can't be ignored. Now, as we have checked the validity of data and familiarized ourselves with it, we can move on to the next stage of the Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining (CRISP-DM) which is modeling.

The questions to be answered at this stage could be for example:

  • What kind of model architecture best fits our data?
  • How well does the model perform technically?
  • Could we improve that performance?
  • How the performance of the model is evaluated?

Machine learning is a subfield of artificial intelligence which provides automatic, objective and data-driven techniques for modeling the data. The machine learning algorithms aim to learn from data to make predictions. The two main branches of it are supervised learning and unsupervised learning. In this exercise, we are going to use the former -- supervised learning -- for classification and regression tasks.

For classification, data remains the same as in the previous exercise, but I've already cleaned it up for you. Some data pre-processing steps are still required to ensure that it's in an appropriate format, so that models can learn something from it. Even though we are not doing any major data exploration nor data preparation here this time, you should never forget it in your future data analyses.

1. Classification using k-nearest neighbors

We start exploring the world of data modeling by using K-Nearest Neightbors (k-NN) algorithm. The k-NN algorithm is one of the classic supervised machine learning algorithms. It assumes that similar points are close to each other.

In our case, we'll use the k-NN algorithm to predict the presence of cardiovascular disease using all the other variables as features in the given data set. So, the target variable is cardio.

But first, we need data for the task. The code for loading the data into the environment is provided for you. The code should work, but make sure, that you have the csv file of the data in the same directory where you have this notebook file.

We have the data so let's make use of it.

To teach the k-NN algorithm (or any kind of machine learning algorithm) to recognize patterns, we are going to need training data. But to test how well a model possibly learned those patterns, we'll need test data which is new and unseen for the trained model. Keep in mind that the test set is not shown for the model before we are actually done with training.

So, to find the estimate for the performance of a model, we are going to use this train-test split. "Split" because we literally split the data into two sets.

Sometimes stratification needs to be considered. It can be used to ensure that train and test sets contain the same proportions of samples of each target class as the original data set.

In [91]:
### Code - Standardization
# selecting numeric features from training and testing set
numeric_feature_columns = ['age','height','weight','ap_hi','ap_lo']
training_numeric_features = training_features[numeric_feature_columns]
testing_numeric_features = testing_features[numeric_feature_columns]

# scaling the numeric features in training and testing set
scaler = StandardScaler()
standardized_training_features = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(training_numeric_features), columns=numeric_feature_columns)
standardized_testing_features = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(testing_numeric_features), columns=numeric_feature_columns)

# merging non numeric features with the new scaled training and testing set
standardized_training_features = pd.concat([standardized_training_features, training_features.loc[:, ~training_features.columns.isin(numeric_feature_columns)].reset_index()], axis=1)
standardized_testing_features = pd.concat([standardized_testing_features, testing_features.loc[:, ~testing_features.columns.isin(numeric_feature_columns)].reset_index()], axis=1)

# setting the original index
standardized_training_features.set_index('index', inplace=True)
standardized_testing_features.set_index('index', inplace=True)

*Data with different scales can influence each other, using standardization, data with a high scale and lower scale are transformed to have a same scale so that it can be analysed easily. In our case, 'age' has a higher scale as compared to the other numeric features, therefore, it is important to scale the features. Since K-NN follows a distance based approach, I think scaling can improve the performance of the model.*

2. Classification accuracy using leave-one-out cross validation

Even thought the train-test split gives us an unbiased estimate of the performance, we only evaluate the model one time. Especially with very small data sets, a test set will be very small. How can we be sure that the evaluation is accurate with this small test set and not just a good (or bad) luck? And what if we'd like to compare two models and the other seems to be better -- how can we be sure that it's not just a coincidence?

Well, there's a great help available and it's called cross-validation. This time, we'll take a look at leave-one-out cross-validation.

*Exercise 2 A)*

Describe in your own words, how leave-one-out cross validation works? How does it actually differ from the basic train-test split?

*Leave one out is one of the cross validation techniques where the number of folds are equal to the number of observations in our dataset. As the name suggests, it selects just one instance from the dataset for testing and the remaining instances are used for training of the model, this step is repeated for each instance. In genral, for the i-th instance, it uses the i-th instance for testing and every other instance (excluding the i-th) for training. On the other hand, in case of basic train-test split, we split the data once and the accuracy is also calculated one. Leave one out works the same way as the code above for 1000 train-test split, only difference being the total number of train-test split will be equal to the number of instances in the dataset and the test size will always be one.*

5. Comparison of ridge regression and kNN regression

The previous exercises were about classification. Now, we are ready to see another kind of supervised learning - regression. We're going to use Ridge Regression and K-Nearest Neighbors Regression, and compare the performances of these models.

To make this exercise more intuitively, let's change the data to another somewhat famous dataset called The Boston Housing Dataset. The Boston Housing Dataset is a derived from information collected by the U.S. Census Service concerning housing in the area of Boston, Massachusetts. Let's have a quick peek at the variables:

  • CRIM - per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
  • CHAS - Charles River dummy variable (1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX - nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM - average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
  • DIS - weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
  • RAD - index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
  • PTRATIO - pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • B - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
  • LSTAT - % lower status of the population
  • MEDV - Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000's

No worries if the variables don't make a lot of sense. However, the object is to predict the median house value. So the target variable is now MEDV and all the others are features.

*1. For regression model evaluation, we use 'neg_mean_absolute_error' as the scoring parameter. As it is mentioned on the sklearn documentation that "All scorer objects follow the convention that higher return values are better than lower return values." Therefore in our case, the knn regression model (best mean_test_score = -2.111260) is far better than the ridge regression model (best mean_test_score = -11.776573)
2. MAE calculates the average error between the predictions and actual value of y, hence, the lower the MAE, the better the model performs. In our case, knn regression model has a lower MAE (2.19) as compared to ridge regression model (2.60), thus we can say that knn is better than ridge regression and it is also proved by the accuracy of the models (knn = 76.89% and ridge = 73.64%)*
